## Sensitivity Prediction (mV/V)

Using a half-bridge Wheatstone configuration, the output is estimated by

<div style="background:#f6f8fa; padding:12px; border-radius:6px;">
V<sub>out</sub> / V<sub>in</sub> ≈ (Gauge Factor × 2 × Strain) / 4  
<br>with Gauge Factor ≈ 2.05 and ε ≈ 1.055 × 10⁻³.
</div>

Using the FEM strain at the gauge location, the predicted sensitivity is:

**Final Sensitivity:** ≥ **1.0 mV/V** at 600 in·lbf  

This satisfies the project requirement and improves on the baseline design by more than a factor of two.

---

## Strain Gauge Selection

**Selected Gauge:** Vishay EA-06-125BZ-350  
**Type:** Linear foil strain gauge, 350 Ω, Gauge Factor ≈ 2.05  

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Gauge Parameter</th><th>Value</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Grid Length</td><td>3.18 mm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Grid Width</td><td>1.57 mm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Pattern Type</td><td>Linear</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

The grid dimensions and resistance are compatible with the available mounting area and the strain levels predicted in the FEM model, supporting reliable half-bridge instrumentation at the reduced section.

---

## Conclusion

The final torque-wrench configuration:

- Meets structural, fatigue, and fracture safety criteria for the specified loading  
- Achieves more than double the baseline strain-gauge sensitivity  
- Produces clean, predictable strain fields suitable for a half-bridge Wheatstone circuit  
- Demonstrates a full workflow from analytical beam theory through CAD, material selection, and FEM verification  

This design process validates the improved geometry as a practical, instrumented torque wrench suitable for experimental use and strain-based torque measurement.

